 LONDON, May 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Off-spinner Graeme Swann followed his maiden test fifty with two wickets off consecutive balls as England took control of the first test against West Indies at Lord's on Thursday. At tea on the second day West Indies were 99 for four in their first innings in reply to England's 377 all out. Swann struck nine fours in an ebullient unbeaten 63 from 89 balls, bringing up his half-century with a hooked six over square-leg off Lionel Baker. He was then surprisingly thrown the new ball by Andrew Strauss after Stuart Broad had opened from the Nursery End, bowling two overs for seven runs before giving way to James Anderson. Returning for a second spell, Swann bowled Devon Smith for 46 before capturing the cherished wicket of Shivnarine Chanderpaul with his next delivery, caught by Paul Collingwood at slip in the final over before the interval. Broad justified his elevation to first-choice opening bowler by regularly reaching 145 kms an hour and dismissing West Indies captain Chris Gayle (28 from 34 balls) and Ramnaresh Sarwan (13). West Indies fast bowler Fidel Edwards earlier completed impressive figures of six for 92 and England's Ravi Bopara made 
